<TEXT>
a national union of the homeless said monday 
it had seized at least seven vacant governmentowned houses as 
part of a national protest against housing policies 
the national union of the homeless which claims 18000 homeless 
and formerly homeless members in 16 cities said it took five 
houses in philadelphia and one each in alexandria va and detroit 
police prevented a move to take a house in new york city 
the philadelphiabased union said it also planned takeovers in 
minneapolis chicago and washington dc coordinators of those 
groups either didnt have information on the activities or 
couldnt be contacted monday night because of disconnected 
telephones 
anna kontradas a senior adviser to housing and urban 
development secretary jack kemp didnt address the unions actions 
directly but said in a statement that huds immediate goal is to 
help provide both housing and supportive services to those who are 
homeless today 
we feel like its insane to have boardedup houses when so 
many people are homeless said ronald darnaby of the philadelphia 
union which took over five homes 
in new york about 30 members of the tent city chapter of the 
union were thwarted by police in their attempt to take a house 
said union member renaldo casanova he said two groups members were 
arrested 
casanova 43 defended the groups actions 
i think it is against the law to let people live in the 
streets he said 
in northern virginia and in detroit groups reportedly occupied 
a vacant house no further details were available 
a member of the tucson union of homeless in arizona said his 
group plans to set up a homeless camp next week in front of a 
federal building located downtown 
the union wants a number of changes in national policies 
including hud allocation of 50000 homes it owns to the homeless 
we are sick and tired of empty promises union president 
leona smith said 
the government is more committed to bailing out mismanaged 
savings and loans banks than to saving and restoring the lives of 
people who are homeless chronically unemployed and who are being 
pressed into a permanent underclass status she said 
the organization also wants half of all community development 
block grant money earmarked for remodeling or new construction of 
lowincome housing and for more rent subsidies 
the coordinator for the homeless for huds regional office in 
philadelphia pat mulligan said his agency considered the seizures 
illegal trespassing but said officials had not decided how to 
respond 
city officials sent in building inspectors but no police 
officers 
police lt ed kachigian said the city had referred the seizures 
to hud and would not act against the homeless unless hud requested 
police assistance 
darnaby said the coalition checked with huds inventory to 
identify houses for sale then discussed the proposed seizures with 
community leaders and neighborhood clergy 
the twostory houses would house two families each none of the 
houses had utilities darnaby said 
inside one of the houses on monday morning protesters and 
homeless people wearing coats huddled around kerosene heaters and 
sipped hot drinks while about 20 other members picketed the 
sidewalks outside 
well stay as long as it takes said charles thompson 
across the street at chew transmission center an employee who 
would only identify himself as ed said he had considered buying the 
house from hud and said the coalition should not be allowed to 
seize the house 
i think they should have to pay for it he said 
city housing commissioner ed schwartz said his department would 
not try to force the squatters out 
schwartz said he was willing to act as a mediator between 
dignity shelter which is part of the union and hud a role he 
played two years ago when the group seized several houses hud 
later sold those houses to dignity shelter 
mulligan said the federal agency gives priority to shelter 
groups when selling houses and offers the groups leases for 1 a 
year 
</TEXT>
