<TEXT>
more than a thousand miles from the mexican 
border is perhaps the nations unlikeliest drug battlefield a 
small city in a farming valley that is being compared to miami and 
new york 
drug dealers riding a sort of underground railroad to wealth 
have turned yakima county into the heroin and cocaine trafficking 
capital of the pacific northwest 
traveling on longestablished migrant farmworker routes from 
deep inside mexico they have brought death and disrepute 
the sound of an ak47 assault rifle shatters the evening calm 
one night on another a mans arm is chopped off with a machete 
apparently the fallout from a soured drug deal us drug 
enforcement administration agents arrest entire families and 
police use spotlights to illuminate known drug houses 
once notable mostly for growing many of the nations apples 
yakima county has become a front line in the nations war on drugs 
there is a war between the people of this city and the drug 
cartels says county commissioner graham tollefson this is not 
a war we are capable of winning ourselves 
william bennett the federal drug czar visited the city of 
50000 people last october and was astonished said his spokesman 
david robb 
secretary bennett came away with the feeling that for a 
community its size there was clearly something wrong there robb 
said in a telephone interview from washington it definitely 
jumps off the map 
sen brock adams dwash hoping to use bennetts reaction to 
gain more dea agents and federal resources asked that yakima 
county be designated a highintensity drug trafficking area 
bennett instead selected new york city miami los angeles 
houston and the southwest border region but in a letter to adams 
his office acknowledged the yakima areas problem and promised more 
help 
yakima county has become a warehouse and wholesale distribution 
point for drugs eventually consumed in other communities said 
robert dreisbach head of the deas office here 
when the dea opened its fulltime office in 1986 agents were 
amazed by what they found dresibach said 
i never saw anything like it he said 
but perhaps they should not have been surprised 
while yakima county is one of the worlds premier food 
producers supplying the nation with asparagus apples mint 
pears fruit juice and hops for beer the metropolitan area ranked 
fifth from the bottom in per capita income in 1988 in a us bureau 
of labor statistics study 
the countys 186000 residents easily have the states highest 
metropolitan unemployment rate 14 percent in january 
education levels are low and goodpaying jobs are scarce making 
drugdealing an attractive option for those seeking to avoid the 
fields or the fruit row warehouses 
the minority population also is high compared to the rest of the 
state law officers say the countys 17 percent hispanic population 
provides a perfect cover for drugdealers from mexico to move 
freely in and out of the area 
the problem has spread to other counties in central washington 
as well 
franklin county with just 35000 residents has the highest per 
capita felony caseload in the state and a 350000 court budget 
deficit the county seat of pasco was the site of a mass murder in 
1988 in which five men were shot to death in an auto body shop the 
presumed motive was drugs the presumed killers escaped to mexico 
the city of wenatchee 100 miles north has shown signs of 
sprouting as a drug trafficking center 
along with the drugs come violence and an overloaded criminal 
justice system described as near collapse 
drug arrests in yakima jumped from under 300 in 1984 to more 
than 700 in 1988 the new county jail is already 30 percent over 
capacity holding more than 400 prisoners a day 
law officers time their arrests to days when there is available 
jail space dreisbach said prosecutors are bogged down with 
caseloads triple those in nearby cities 
we cant even put people in jail said police officer maria 
schade who for two years has been pursuing streetlevel dealers in 
the citys central business district its got to be a felony or 
a warrant 
more troubling violent crime has become almost commonplace 
there were 23 murders in the county last year following a record 
28 the year before as recently as 1984 only nine murders were 
recorded 
not coincidentally requests from county residents for gun 
permits jumped from 411 in 1986 to 2256 in 1989 sheriff doug 
blair said 
police chief pleas green says nearly all the murders are 
drugrelated and believes its only a matter of time before one of 
his officers is killed 
we have stepped up training in officer survival techniques 
he said 
an example of the scope of the areas drug trade was last 
augusts dea raid that broke up two longtime drugdealing families 
in the yakima valley and produced 18 arrests in yakima tacoma 
seattle and portland ore 
for 15 years the multigeneration drug families had provided up 
to 200 kilograms of cocaine a month to the seattle and portland 
areas dreisbach said 
the operation was not that sophisticated but provided another 
example of the drug pipeline police have come to know and fear 
they get into a car and drive it south dreisbach said 
they put drugs in the car and drive it north 
</TEXT>
