<TEXT>
like many residents auto parts dealer 
jose chavez has developed a fear of teenagers in his crimeplagued 
colonia near the south texas border 
his advice for visitors if you stop there at nighttime and 
you see a bunch of kids you better not stop 
they might be tricity bombers a youth gang claiming lopezville 
as its territory other gangs roam many of hidalgo countys rural 
colonias the scores of impoverished subdivisions where migrant 
farm workers live along unpaved streets without adequate water 
sewers or drainage 
in this farming region separated from the rest of the country by 
huge ranches people wonder how they ended up with a social problem 
considered symptomatic of bigcity angst and alienation 
how did they get an asphalt jungle in a place where the 
streets arent even paved 
officials say the lower rio grande valleys gangs remain 
relatively unsophisticated yet just as in los angeles chicago 
and other cities they steal fight and attack enemies windows 
with rocks and bullets 
sometimes they kill in january a gunfight between what police 
said were rival gang members left two young men dead in the town of 
san juan 
it is the despair of poverty some say that leads to gang 
membership along with a high school dropout rate that hovers 
around 50 percent 
kids are real bored man said gabriel benavides a 
17yearold still in school who has been named by the hildago 
county sheriffs department as a tricity bombers leader 
the gang which claims about 200 members is named for the 
cities of pharr san juan and alamo which share a school district 
the spraypainted tcb initials show up everywhere in lopezville 
its like having an outside family were all brothers 
benavides said putting his fist on his heart with the index and 
pinky fingers extended the tcb salute 
they dont like to fight he said but cautioned i have a 
tendency to cause pain if you give me trouble i have a tendency 
to cause pain if you dont mess with me i wont give you pain 
tcb member jorge alberto cantu 20 remains in jail without 
bond accused in the shooting deaths of two males who authorities 
said belonged to a gang called the spoilers tcb members confrnted 
a group of spoilers outside a san juan video arcade the night of 
jan 5 said police chief rene lizcano 
parents of the victims 14yearold guadalupe gonzalez jr and 
his 21yearold cousin miguel ojeda said neither belonged to a 
gang 
he was going to get married a week later oralia ojeda said 
of her son 
chavez gave up on keeping glass in the windows at his small 
store joes auto parts gang members would throw rocks through 
them in revenge every time he painted over the graffiti they 
sprayed on his storefront he said now the windows are covered 
with heavy sheets of plywood 
one night a brick sailed through the front window of chavezs 
house and hit his wife in the head he said another day someone 
fired shots into the cab of his truck 
a lot of these people they dont say nothing because theyre 
afraid these kids will come and do something at their house at 
night while theyre asleep chavez said 
two years ago five area gang members were convicted of beating 
a 27yearold man to death with a baseball bat outside a 
convenience store they left his 33yearold brother with permanent 
brain damage said chief deputy bob davis of the sheriffs 
department 
apparently it wasnt over anything davis said these 
guys were on their turf 
davis estimates about 25 gangs operate in the countys rural 
areas covered by only seven patrol cars gang members smashed the 
windows out of four patrol cars in a melee last halloween 
some residents say the gangs have been around for nearly a 
decade but drew authorities attention only after the cars were 
attacked 
the developments worry j michael olivero a criminal justice 
professor at the university of texaspan american in edinburg 
olivero who studied gangs in the chicago area believes the 
south texas groups could become sophisticated crime rings involved 
in extortion drug trafficking and other crimes typical of urban 
gangs 
they found a kid with an uzi olivero said the things 
arent cheap 
graffiti representing california and illinois gangs has started 
appearing on area walls which olivero said could result from 
children of migrant farm families traveling to other states 
community leaders have been meeting recently to address the gang 
problem and say parks and jobs would help kids stay out of trouble 
school officials meanwhile have promised a late afternoon bus 
route to give students in outlying areas a chance to participate in 
extracurricular activities 
chris willingham head counselor at the local high school said 
the transient lives of migrant farm workers keep many children 
offbalance at school many arrive late in the year and leave 
early she said 
were going to have to address the educational needs of these 
kids olivero said and were going to have to get them water 
and get them roads and things like that to facilitate a sense of 
pride kids who are integrated with family church and school dont 
join gangs 
but while lizcano the san juan police chief acknowledges the 
county has a problem he rejects the theory that gangs are fostered 
by poverty and hopelessness 
i grew up in a colonia myself he said and im a chief of 
police 
