<TEXT>
gen augusto pinochet is taking his final 
bows declaring democracy restored after a coup and more than 16 
years in power but the civilians who will follow him say the job 
has just begun 
pinochet says he is leaving a thriving orderly nation to 
presidentelect patricio aylwin who takes office march 11 
we promised to restore democracy and we have done it 
pinochet said recently on a farewell tour of this narrow 
3000milelong nation on south americas west coast we gave it 
the indispensable stability required for living in peace freedom 
and solidarity 
his critics dont see it that way 
the transition to democracy will be very very hard but the 
alternative to tackling the difficulties is remaining under a 
dictatorship said jorge arrate head of the socialist party 
his party is prominent in aylwins centerleft coalition arrate 
and others in the alliance say they are inheriting a powder keg of 
social problems long ignored or suppressed by pinochets military 
government 
they say the new administration will be hardpressed by the need 
for more social services wage demands from labor and the desire 
for justice in cases of human rights abuses 
pinochet 74 insists on retaining command of the 60000man 
army for up to eight more years as permitted by the 1980 
constitution his government wrote 
he also hints at an eventual return to power and has not ruled 
out running in the 1994 election at public gatherings in the 
waning days of his presidency supporters can be heard shouting 
youll be back soon or until 1994 
the general held a referendum in 1988 trying to get approval 
for an eightyear extension of his presidency but the voters said 
no that forced him to call an election and aylwin a 71yearold 
centrist christian democrat got 55 percent of the vote 
small but enthusiastic crowds have turned out for pinochets 
farewell tour which uses the slogan mission accomplished 
pinochet proudly tells them that chile enjoys one of latin 
americas healthiest economies one of its lowest inflation rates 
about 20 percent a year and a gross national product that has 
grown steadily for six years 
he says the political and social disorder that was rampant when 
he overthrew the elected government of president salvador allende 
an avowed marxist in september 1973 has been replaced by an 
orderly society 
the 1980 constitution provides an institutional bulwark against 
chaos or a communist threat according to pinochet 
critics however consider the claims unfounded and the tour a 
disgrace 
this idea that we have to express our gratitude its 
absurd arrate said hes the only chilean president ever to 
stage a farewell carnival 
arrate said pinochets claim to have laid the institutional 
groundwork for democracy was contradicted by lastminute laws that 
cut aylwins authority and gave armed forces unprecedented 
autonomy among other changes 
the new government plans to modify many of the laws but the 
problem is you lose time in undoing those things said ricardo 
ffrenchdavis an economist with aylwins christian democratic 
party 
he said pinochets pride in the economic growth of the last six 
years is arbitrary like so many arbitrary things that have 
occurred under this government 
pinochet also must take responsibility for the worst recession 
in latin america in the early 1980s when production in chile 
fell by more than 13 percent and unemployment soared to 20 percent 
or more ffrenchdavis said 
improvement since then has represented recovery with very 
little growth the economist said and poor people have not had a 
proper share in it 
if you take the top 20 percent of the population and the 
bottom 20 percent the gap has been growing all these years he 
said 
ffrenchdavis said there is a desperate need for better public 
education and health services but he and other economists in 
aylwins camp praise the existing freemarket exportoriented 
economic program and do not plan major changes 
to distribute chiles wealth the economy must grow and for 
the economy to grow you must have stability he said 
most unions were suppressed under pinochet and aylwin also 
expects a chorus of demands for higher wages but arrate said 
workers and the poor must not expect too much 
we cant correct from one day to the next all the inequities 
that have accumulated during 16 years he said all we can do 
is give signs that the government has changed its tendency 
democracy is expected to bring a cry for justice in hundreds of 
pending cases of alleged human rights violations by security 
forces at least 700 people disappeared after the coup and 
thousands were jailed and tortured 
demands by rights groups for swift and severe punishment 
probably will not be met aylwin has stressed the need for national 
reconciliation and said justice must be tempered by a spirit of 
pardon 
</TEXT>
