a former president of brandeis univesity and 
his wife are suspected to be among the americans killed in last 
weeks fire at a luxury hotel a us embassy spokeswoman said 
sunday 
the spokeswoman said the bodies of marver bernstein and his wife 
were believed to be in the cairo morgue but she could not confirm 
the deaths until a medical report was received so far she said 
they are listed as unaccounted for 
dr kamal elsaadani of cairos central morgue said friday that 
a man with a similar name was among the dead and that the body of 
an unidentified woman was thought to be that of his wife 
if confirmed the deaths would bring to four the number of 
americans killed in the hotel fire thursday at the heliopolis 
sheraton in which 17 people died 
according to the washington post bernstein 71 was dean of the 
woodrow wilson school of public and international affairs at 
princeton university before serving as president of brandeis in 
waltham mass from 1972 to 1983 he then joined the faculty of 
the georgetown school of foreign service where he taught both 
politics and philosophy and coordinated the schools american 
courses program 
after his retirement from georgetown last year he remained as a 
lecturer bernstein born in mankato minn and sheva rosenthal a 
native of st paul minn married in 1943 the paper said 
also sunday police said all cairo hotels will be checked for 
adequate firefighting equipment 
maj gen fahr eldin khaled head of the tourist police said a 
police committee would check all hotels whether or not they have 
canvas tents similar to the one at the sheraton where the fire 
started 
this committee will prepare a comprehensive report which will 
be presented to the tourism minister to take suitable procedures so 
that such accidents do not happen in egypt again khaled said 
according to the official middle east news agency 
sheraton officials have insisted that a fire alarm was sounded 
when the fire spread from its garden tent restaurant to the hotel 
building itself early thursday 
they said hotel workers tried to put out the blaze with 
extinguishers but strong winds caused it to spread so quickly it 
became uncontrollable 
survivors said there was no fire alarm or sprinkler system 
egyptian officials have said the canvas tents popular at most 
luxury hotels in egypt are illegal because they are fire hazards 
but spokesmen for four major hotels in cairo contacted by the 
associated press said their tents had adequate safety precautions 
and there was no plan to dismantle them 
it was not immediately clear if officials would ban the tents 
which usually house restaurants or nightclubs 
tourism is one of egypts main sources of foreign currency in 
1989 24 million tourists visited egypt bringing 23 billion 
into the country according to official figures 
