librarians are asking congress to guarantee 
public access to information generated by the nations largest 
compiler of facts the government itself 
the american library association says the bush administration so 
far hasnt lived up to a promise to reverse reagan administration 
policies which curtailed how much information the government 
gathers and restricted its distribution 
specifically the 50000member association is concerned that 
making information available through electronic means and not on 
paper could wind up limiting access or costing the user for what 
he now gets free 
and the librarians worry about the practice of letting private 
enterprise assume the responsibility of disseminating government 
information in hopes of turning a profit 
a system of information haves and havenots could be 
created big business customers who can afford to buy while 
students individuals libraries and others cannot ala president 
patricia wilson berger testified last month before the senate 
government affairs committee 
the committee is considering legislation reexamining the 
governments information distribution policies 
the association fears that the proposed bill could require 
libraries to pay for information they now get free from the 
government it would permit agencies to require libraries to share 
distribution costs of electronically relayed information 
the taxpayer already has paid to gather and generate and 
maintain this information and shouldnt be asked to pay again to 
get access to it said eileen cooke the alas washington 
representative 
ms berger said she welcomes new technologies which could 
enhance access to information but added they are equally 
capable of erecting artificial barriers to citizens rights to 
know 
she said the problem arises when libraries lack equipment 
software indexes finding aids trained staff and expertise in the 
use of data bases 
since the earliest days of the republic ms berger 
testified the federal government has provided ways to inform the 
public of its activities and to collect information essential to 
its operations today it is the largest collector and publisher of 
information in the united states 
but reagan administration guidelines adopted in 1985 encouraged 
the distribution of government information through private 
enterprise the guidelines also pared the governments publication 
lists 
thousands of publications were scrapped data collection 
programs were scaled back libraries of many federal agencies were 
turned over to private management companies and access to the 
documents of regulatory agencies was made far more difficult the 
ala said 
under the bush administration the omb has promised to revise 
these information policies the association said so far 
however no concrete action has resulted 
a law passed in 1858 requires the government to make its 
publications available to 1346 depository libraries around the 
country in addition 51 regional depositories are required to get 
and keep every publication issued by the government printing 
office last year the gpo distributed 27 million copies of 68000 
different publications to the depository libraries 
as an example of the problem the ala cites an electronic data 
base operated by the agriculture department to furnish commodity 
statistical economic and other agricultural reports 
until 1985 the department released the information through a 
university of nebraska computer system then under new omb 
guidelines the government signed an exclusive contract giving the 
information to martin marietta data systems which sells access to 
it 
according to the ala information once distributed free or at 
nominal costs through the university of nebraska to depository 
libraries now costs 45 an hour from martin marietta or as much as 
96 an hour from clients which get the information from martin 
marietta and redistribute it 
