<TEXT>
town meetings usually come and go 
without much of a stir in this quiet coastal community but a plan 
to abolish local taxes promises to breathe new life into yankee 
democracy this year 
a lot of people are going who wouldnt normally be there 
said mark gross one of 1200 residents in the blueberrycanning 
community 
the proposal to scrap property taxes in 1991 and replace them 
with voluntary contributions and user fees has got a lot of 
people around town a little nervous said gross who calls the 
plan a lot of crazy ideas 
but to royce perkins who is leading the taxfreedom charge from 
his handbuilt log home deep in the woods scuttling taxes seems as 
natural as lighting a fire in a woodburning stove or skinning a 
weasel 
perkins 53 a father of five whose 150 acres roll over scenic 
woodlands along a jagged coastal peninsula envisions a system in 
which noncompulsory payments and payasyougo fees finance only 
those services that people really want and really need 
one of the great joys of life is to own your own home outright 
and clear but when you have taxes against your home its like a 
constant mortgage he said property taxation is like holding a 
sword over the land 
a wildlife biologist and salmon fisherman in alaska for about 20 
years perkins returned with his family to his native environs 
several years ago also a former teacher he educates his children 
at home he runs the local landfill and also operates an 
earthmoving business 
his proposal is on the agenda for tuesdays town meeting because 
35 people five more than the minimum needed signed a petition 
the man who oversees penobscots 12 million budget 
selectmens board chairman jim henry said hes never heard of such 
an extreme plan he said hell definitely be among those taking a 
stand against it tuesday 
its too idealistic said henry 
still even henry allows that i love the notion of having no 
taxes and he believes the debate among taxpayers is unquestionably 
healthy 
now people know what services the town provides what they 
would lose and what they would have to pay for whereas before 
they paid their taxes and didnt ask questions said henry 
of the total budget 1 million goes to the schools and the 
rest is divided among services that include road maintenance a 
volunteer fire department landfill general government expenses 
and street lights 
perkins sees the string of street lights in the center of 
penobscot a new england tableau of handsome clapboard homes 
church school and town hall overlooking the bay and river by the 
same name as an example of a municipal service that only the 
handful of its users should pay for 
as for the bigticket question of education perkins says the 
state should ultimately pick up the entire tab and issue vouchers 
so that families can send their children to the schools of their 
choice 
his neighbors remain skeptical 
a lot of people if they dont have to pay theyre not going 
to pay said gross 
are you going to put tolls on our town roads and a toll booth 
at the town dump asked kenneth reynolds a fish dealer 
one of the biggest fears is the prospect of being hit with huge 
school bills if parents of students are forced to support the 
schools alone 
in my occupation i couldnt pay to educate my children and 
many others couldnt said rev james robertson of the south 
penobscot baptist church 
perkins said he has received letters of support from people in 
other states but he acknowledged that support among townspeople 
appears light at best but win or lose he said he is gratified his 
oneman tax revolt has at least spurred civic activism 
ive had several say i havent been to a town meeting in 20 
years but im going this time he said 
</TEXT>
