<TEXT>
the soviet union is running out of tobacco to 
meet the rising demands of cigarette smokers according to an 
agriculture department report 
although the soviet union is the worlds thirdlargest tobacco 
producer this years harvest is expected to be only 215000 metric 
tons unchanged from 1989 the peak was 350000 tons in 1985 only 
china and the united states produce more 
major acreage reductions are taking place in moldavia the 
major tobacco producing republic in order to increase food 
production the report said although the soviet government 
calls for a mandatory sixmonth supply of tobacco limited supplies 
have reduced stock levels to barely a threemonth supply 
since 1970 tobacco smoking in all forms has increased 70 
percent according to official soviet figures in 1988 it was 
estimated that there were 70 million smokers spending an 
equivalent of 11 billion annually 
a government antismoking campaign has been waged since soviet 
leader mikhail gorbachev came to power including a smoking ban on 
all domestic air flights and in some work places 
however public interest in reducing the level of smoking 
seems low the report said smoking is quite acceptable in the 
soviet society even with the awareness of its potential hazards 
domestic demand for tobacco increase slightly in 1988 with retail 
sales growing 2 percent 
the report was written by laura r davis a tobacco analyst in 
the departments foreign agricultural service and was included 
last week in a review of the world tobacco situation 
currently the soviets rely on other centrally planned countries 
for imports of cigarettes and other manufactured tobacco products 
the report said 
in 1988 almost 55 billion cigarettes were imported with more 
than 95 percent coming from bulgaria residual suppliers included 
cuba india switzerland the netherlands and the united states 
but imports of unmanufactured tobacco leaf has declined to less 
than half of the peak years in the early 1980s 
comparatively us tobacco production last year was 641460 
metric tons about three times larger than soviet output and us 
cigarette production at 685 billion pieces last year was 80 
percent larger than the 380 billion produced by the soviet union in 
1988 
what happens next is uncertain the report said lacking hard 
currency the soviet union will probably continue importing tobacco 
and tobacco products through reciprocal agreements 
although the government has thus far been unsuccessful in 
curtailing cigarette consumption future attempts may succeed in 
lowering the demand for tobacco products the report said 
meanwhile the soviet unions reduction in tobacco production and 
imports while consumer demand remains high will continue to draw 
down inventories 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
making changes in the amount of cropland 
farmers must idle in order to qualify for federal price support 
benefits can have little effect on total production according to 
an agriculture department report 
the annual landidling is provided by the acreage reduction 
program or arp in the various annual commodity programs 
to qualify for benefits farmers might have to idle 5 percent or 
10 percent or even 40 percent of their acreage for a specific 
crop under the usual arrangements farmers are not paid for land 
idled in the arp but have to comply if they want price supports and 
deficiency payments on the remainder 
the departments economic research service said in the march 
issue of agricultural outlook magazine that switching arp levels in 
the feed grain program would produced mixed results 
theoretically it said if the arp was increased to 40 percent 
from 5 percent the previous year federal spending would be reduced 
by 47 billion and net farm income by 28 billion 
but feed grain production mainly corn would be reduced by 
only about 5 percent 
falling program participation rates combined with more 
intensive use of permitted acres are behind these results the 
report said 
the participation rate in the programs was said to be the most 
important variable in switching to different arps 
participation in the corn program for example would drop 
from 80 percent to 43 percent if the feed grain arp were raised 
from 5 percent to 50 percent the report said 
in all with a 50 percent arp for feed grain the program 
acreage would decline to 24 million acres from nearly 78 million 
</TEXT>
