<TEXT>
a huge poaching raid that startled this 
poor town of 800 a year ago may actually have helped prompt an 
artistic and economic renaissance some community leaders say 
a local artist is making a religious shrine two 
bedandbreakfasts have opened empty buildings are being 
renovated plans are being made for cottage industries using the 
skills of local artisans 
allen c manzanares director of the statefunded costilla 
county economic development council inc thinks the raid has had a 
positive effect on a town where one of every four or five people is 
unemployed 
it caught the attention of the rest of the state and of gov 
roy romer who got funding for development council said 
manzanares whose family has lived here for many generations as 
have most san luis families 
we want to put it behind us and i think generally we have 
he said the community has started to recover from it how do 
we turn something negative into a positive 
last march 6 more than 100 state and federal wildlife officials 
converged on san luis and nearby chama and fort garland they 
arrested 57 alleged poachers in the culmination of a 2year sting 
an undercover officer had posed as a taxidermist and wild game 
processor set up shop and bought elk deer bear and other game 
hides and carcasses many taken out of season as well as 
endangered birds of prey 
of the 57 people arrested the cases of three are still pending 
charges against four were dismissed and seven were fined and 
sentenced to prison terms of up to eight months the others pleaded 
guilty and were fined 
san luis in an arid valley at 7900 feet was founded in 1851 
by descendants of spanish colonists it is colorados oldest town 
and like neighboring san pablo san pedro and san francisco the 
areas heritage culture and geography have isolated it 
the closeknit community remains nearly 90 percent hispanic 
people here take care of each other said the rev patrick 
valdez the roman catholic priest who is one of the chief 
architects of the towns renaissance 
there is no hunger but there is poverty if there is an 
illness or a death they do take care of each other 
san luis awakening has come from within 
valdez has renovated a convent left in disarray since the 1950s 
turning it into a handicraft gallery and a bed and breakfast 
appropriately called el convento 
the gallery is the incubator of a whole series of cottage 
industries valdez said 
what i anticipate is that the artisans will start off here and 
when they get big enough they will be able to open their own 
businesses and open their extra rooms into shops or their garages 
into workshops he said 
also planned are the towns first motel and a furniture factory 
employing local artisans the town sponsored workshops for artists 
and artisans last summer and plans more this summer 
at the center of activity is a shrine being built on a hill 
overlooking the village the stations of the cross images that 
depict christs final suffering crucifixion and burial will be 
placed along a nearly milelong path that hairpins to the top of a 
volcanic rockstrewn mesa west of town 
the stations to be dedicated in may are being rendered in 
bronze by artist huberto maestas who also plans to open a san luis 
foundry that will employ several residents 
valdez saw the poaching case as a setback to an overdue economic 
recovery for the region but said im very optimistic about the 
future 
i think it the recovery was going to happen i think the 
raid was a stumbling block in our way that we have to jump over 
and it would have been better if it hadnt ever happened 
