up to 10000 mongolians rallied in their capital 
in the largest gathering yet of opposition groups seeking 
democratic reform in the worlds secondoldest communist country a 
foreign source said today 
at sundays rally in ulan bator representatives of the social 
democratic movement announced formation of mongolias second 
opposition party the social democratic party said the source who 
spoke on condition he not be identified 
unlike the mongolian democratic party which was formed last 
month and advocates bringing the country to a higher state of 
socialism the social democrats favor an entirely new political 
and economic structure based on an end to the communist monopoly on 
power and dependency on the soviet union 
the two groups are the most active of the halfdozen unofficial 
political organizations that have sprung up in the past 2 months 
in mongolia a vast pastoral land of 2 million people ruled by the 
communist party since 1921 and long a soviet client state 
sundays rally was the sixth since late december 
some 800010000 people gathered at about noon in front of the 
lenin museum then marched to the great peoples hural or 
parliament on central sukhbator square to present a petition to 
the government 
rallies and demonstrations have been banned at the square but 
there was no attempt to disperse the crowd that gathered there for 
about an hour before returning to the lenin museum it was the 
second time an opposition rally has been held there despite the ban 
the protesters delivered a joint petition to the government 
demanding a special congress of the communist party formation of a 
new party central committee promulgation of a new election law and 
election of new deputies to the hural 
the petition set a deadline of wednesday for the government to 
respond but did not say what would happen if there is no response 
the source said 
speakers reiterated calls for quicker reform and for the 
communist party to give up its 69year monopoly on power 
they criticized mongolias economic relations with the soviet 
union alleging that premier dumaagiyn sodnom who just concluded a 
sixday visit to japan is responsible for unfavorable economic 
agreements with the soviet union the groups also called for 
mongolia to withdraw from comecon the soviet bloc trading group 
there was no police or military presence at the rally and 
police even helped direct traffic when the demonstrators marched to 
and from the central square the source said 
