the united states may sharply curtail the granting 
of asylum to nicaraguan refugees because of their nations switch 
to democracy but there is little chance political exiles already 
here will be forced to return 
in theory people granted asylum are subject to review each 
year and could have that status revoked said duke austin 
spokesman for the immigration and naturalization service in 
washington 
but i know of no single case since political asylum has been 
an avenue in the united states when we have involuntarily returned 
someone because conditions in their homeland improved austin 
said its in the law but its never been done 
what is more likely is that new applicants will get tougher 
scrutiny of their applications 
an estimated 80000 to 90000 nicaraguans are now in the united 
states legally including both political and nonpolitical cases 
some exile advocates say twice that number actually live in this 
country if the count includes illegal immigrants many of whom 
were hoping to win political asylum 
in fiscal 1989 the ins granted just under 6000 nicaraguan 
