<TEXT>
the supreme court in a case stemming from the 
1981 settlement of the iran hostage crisis today rejected an 
appeal by a cleveland ohio company seeking to avoid paying 36 
million to iran 
the court without comment let stand what was described as a 
firstofitskind ruling that american courts have authority to 
enforce such payments 
the agreement between the united states and iran that freed 52 
american hostages in 1981 included release by the us government 
of billions of dollars in frozen iranian assets 
the settlement also set up a process permitting those with 
claims against iran to take them to an international tribunal 
the supreme court previously upheld the power of former 
president carter to approve the settlement 
at issue in the appeal acted on today was whether us courts 
can force american companies to pay claims the international 
tribunal has awarded to iran 
gould inc a high technology firm was ordered by the 
international tribunal to pay 36 million and return military 
radio equipment to iran 
iranian officials asked us district judge richard a gadbois 
jr in california to enforce the tribunals decision 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled last year that us 
courts have such power although the appeals court said the 
authority does not derive directly from the 1981 settlement 
the appeals court said the settlement was designed to secure 
payment of claims against iran and provided no specific vehicle 
for the enforcement of awards in favor of iran 
instead the appeals court relied on a 1958 united nations pact 
called the new york convention it provides for enforcement of 
international arbitration awards 
partystates to the convention agree to recognize arbitral 
awards as binding and enforce them in accordance with their own 
rules of procedure the appeals court said noting that the 
united states signed the pact in 1970 
the 36 million payment order against gould qualifies as such 
an arbitral award the appeals court said as it sent the case back 
to gadbois for further review 
gould acquired hoffman export corp in 1978 the hoffman company 
sold electronic military equipment to iran when it was a us ally 
ruled by shah mohammed reza pahlavi 
the case is gould inc vs iran 891103 
