<DOCNO> AP900305-0072 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court ruled today that even when 
police question criminal defendants in violation of their right to 
legal help the responses may be used to contradict trial testimony 
by the defendants 
by a 54 vote in a michigan case the court said the 
constitution does not bar use of such statements when they are used 
by prosecutors to rebut a defendants testimony and impeach the 
accused persons credibility 
the prosecution must not be allowed to build its case against 
a criminal defendant with evidence acquired in contravention of 
constitutional guarantees chief justice william h rehnquist 
wrote for the court 
but use of statements so obtained for impeachment purposes is 
a different matter he said if a defendant exercises his right 
to testify on his own behalf he assumes a reciprocal obligation to 
speak truthfully and accurately 
the court previously has ruled that statements obtained by 
police in violation of a defendants fifth amendment privilege 
against selfincrimination may be used to challenge the defendants 
trial testimony today the court extended those rulings to allow 
use of statements obtained in violation of a defendants sixth 
amendment right to legal representation 
the court ordered further lower court hearings that could lead 
to reinstatment of tyris lemont harveys criminal sexual conduct 
conviction and 6to10year prison sentence 
harvey was accused of sexually assaulting a woman on june 11 
1986 
two months after his arrest and after he was assigned a 
courtappointed lawyer harvey was questioned unlawfully by police 
the police told harvey he did not need to speak to his lawyer first 
because the attorney was going to get a copy of the statement 
anyway 
the statement was used at the trial when prosecutors 
crossexamined harvey to challenge his testimony on the witness 
stand 
harvey testified the woman agreed to remove her clothes 
voluntarily and said the two did not engage in sexual intercourse 
the woman said she was forced to engage in sexual acts 
harveys conviction was overturned by a michigan appeals court 
which ordered a new trial the state court said any statements to 
police as the result of an unlawful interrogation may not be used 
for any purpose at the trial 
rehnquist said the sixth amendment to the constitution 
guaranteeing legal representation to defendants does not prohibit 
use of harveys statement to police as long as it was made 
voluntarily 
we have never prevented all use by the prosecution of 
relevant voluntary statements by a defendant rehnquist said 
the search for truth in a criminal case outweighs the speculative 
possibility that exclusion of evidence might deter future 
violations of rules by the police 
rehnquist was joined by justices byron r white sandra day 
oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
justice john paul stevens in a dissenting opinion said the 
tragedy of todays decision is not merely its denigration of the 
constitutional right at stake it also undermines the principle 
that those who are entrusted with the power of government have the 
same duty to respect and obey the law as the ordinary citizen 
he was joined by justices william j brennan thurgood marshall 
and harry a blackmun 
the case is michigan vs harvey 88512 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

