<TEXT>
at least 500 lawyers walked off their 
jobs and sat on the lawns in front of the supreme court building 
monday to protest what they called human rights violations by the 
government 
the hourlong demonstration organized by the nepal bar 
association brought work in the court to a standstill court 
officials said 
bystanders and visitors to the court were held back from the 
site of the demonstration by riot police 
lawyers say 59 of their colleagues were arrested in the 
governments crackdown on a movement for greater democracy several 
have been released and one alleged police tortured those detained 
for five days i had to sleep on damp floors with only rotten 
food to eat even drinking water was not available said asik ram 
karki 
he said some of those arrested were beaten on the soles of their 
feet 
a nationwide movement was launched feb 18 by the nepali 
congress party and the communist party of nepal demanding the 
restoration of multiparty democracy and an end to a 1961 royal 
decree banning all political parties 
according to the government 12 people have been killed in 
demonstrations and police firing since then but activists say the 
toll is double that figure 
nepals 2yearold experiment with westernstyle democracy ended 
in 1961 when king mahendra father of the present monarch king 
birendra dissovled the government of the nepali congrees party 
accusing it of corruption and poor administration 
the government accuses the multiparty advocates of trying to 
impose their version of democracy on a nation that they say already 
has a working deomcracy 
power in nepal is shared between the king and the nonpartisan 
rashtriya panchayat or national assembly onefifth of the 
panchayats 140 members are nominated by the king the rest are 
elected 
the government of king birendra says the campaign to lift the 
ban on political parties runs counter to a 1980 referendum which 
narrowly voted for retaining the panchayats system of nonpartisan 
membership 
