the head of the union representing mail 
carriers came to the defense of higher postage rates monday a day 
before the postal service was expected to announce plans to raise 
the price of a stamp 
a stamp today in terms of real dollars is cheaper than it 
was in 1971 said vincent r sombrotto president of the national 
association of letter carriers 
the us postal service has scheduled a tuesday news conference 
at which it is expected to announce plans for a rate increase 
affecting all classes of mail 
the new rates would take effect sometime in 1991 probably 
including a 30cent price for firstclass stamps currently the 
firstclass rate is a quarter 
it cost 8 cents to mail a firstclass letter when the current 
postal service was set up in 1971 adjusting for inflation since 
then the cost should of a stamp now should be just what it is 25 
cents sombrotto said 
but he added in 1971 the postal service received several 
million dollars in tax subsidies that have been eliminated if that 
value were included stamps should be selling for 33 cents today 
sombrotto said 
sombrotto said he anticipated that a planned rate increase will 
renew discussions of turning the postal service over to private 
business or allowing private companies to compete in mail delivery 
it would be an absolute disaster if that were to happen he 
said 
the postal system is designed to provide service to everyone in 
the country at the same price he said contending that private 
companies could choose to serve only profitable urban areas 
leaving the costly rural deliveries to the postal service that 
would mean either higher costs for rural residents or taxpayer 
subsidies sombrotto said 
