a man was rescued from a cramped wet 
cave monday 16 hours after he fell 30 feet from a ledge and 
suffered lacerations and broken ribs 
more than 75 rescuers worked through the night to extricate 
aaron howell 20 from the cave on private property about five 
miles west of bloomington 
howell of franklin and two friends entered the cave sunday 
morning he slipped off the ledge about three hours later 
jeff schepper one of howells spelunking partners said howell 
fell about 30 feet and was unconscious for about 10 minutes 
schepper went for help but it took him about two hours to find his 
way out of the cave 
paramedics and cave rescue workers found howell conscious and 
coherent about 1300 feet inside the cave sunday night but had to 
use hand chisels and mallets to clear a path to him at the base of 
the ledge 
it was all hand labor they didnt take any specialized tools 
in said capt paul spicer with the van buren township fire 
department 
its very low paquette said its rocky we have deep 
pools of water theres a lot of obstacles they have to get 
through said don paquette of bloomington grotto a cave 
exploration group 
paramedic jeff rogers who spent about six hours with howell in 
the cave said howell was uncomfortable but in good spirits 
throughout the rescue the temperature in the cave was estimated at 
about 53 degrees 
howell was finally removed from the cave about dawn monday 
he was listed as stable at bloomington hospital with multiple 
lacerations and rib fractures hospital spokeswoman beth maxwell 
said he also suffered hypothermia and dehydration 
