<TEXT>
on a hill overlooking the center of 
vilnius three tall white crosses stand in simple defiance to 
history 
hidden by locals to prevent destruction by the soviets in the 
late 1940s the stone crosses were brought out again last year and 
given their former place of prominence 
the crosses are emblematic of the city of about 400000 people 
that is surrounded by low wooded bluffs and bisected by the 
greengray ribbon of the nera river vilnius has learned to survive 
foreign conquest and reemerge with its essential character intact 
today as electric trolleys whoosh along its stonepaved streets 
past colorful kiosks and centuriesold churches vilnius presents 
an attractive face in contrast to the gray monotony of other soviet 
cities 
as the capital of lithuania the baltic republic incorporated 
into the soviet union in 1940 and now struggling to restore its 
sovereignty vilnius finds itself at the center of a peaceful 
rebellion against soviet control 
the lithuanian communist party officially broke ranks with 
moscow in december and multiparty elections on feb 24 brought to 
office what will be the soviet unions first 
noncommunistdominated parliament its first duty will be to lead 
lithuania back to full independence 
despite the momentous changes the city seems curiously calm and 
rancorless as though it would not be wise to get too excited just 
yet 
on the springlike day last month when the voting took place 
townspeople lounged in lenin square reading books or chatting with 
their grandchildren 
at the center of the park stands the 30foottall statue of 
lenin but his oratorical posture seemed out of place with the 
relaxed mood around him 
if lithuania follows the rest of eastern europe the lenin 
statue may not be standing much longer and the communist party will 
find itself on the sidelines 
the situation is not yet ripe for the communists to leave but 
in the long run yes they will go said kastas kumstys a 
student sharing a park bench with his girlfriend 
they had voted earlier in the day for a professor from the 
sajudis independence movement but kumstys said he had no illusions 
the situation would quickly improve 
my parents had stalinism and now we have a time of everything 
overturning he said i dont think it will be better soon 
what most people talk about is not the elections but the 
terrible state of the shops 
on otherwise elegant gedimino street where a huge placard 
proclaims a lithuania without sovereignty is a lithuania without 
a future scores of saturday shoppers lined up for small green 
oranges being unloaded from moldy boxes marked cuba 
elsewhere in the market barriers kept people back while workers 
filled a stand with grapefruit when the barriers were removed 
shoppers raced to the stand elbowing aside each other as they 
greedily grabbed for the citrus 
at a music store up the street the only records being offered 
for sale were comecon music lps from czechoslovakia cuba 
bulgaria and the soviet union 
the kind of music i like they dont have here said a 
20yearold disgruntled shopper walking out the door 
the young man spoke in russianaccented polish one of the three 
languages of vilnius 
lithuanian is spoken most followed by russian but many 
residents are ethnically polish and retain the language that 
dominated the city then known as wilno when it was part of 
poland from 1920 to 1939 
poland and lithuania were united from 1386 to 1795 and its upper 
classes remained polish into modern times 
marshal jozef pilsudski so loved his home town that he conquered 
it for newly restored poland in one of the small wars that followed 
the collapse of the russian empire in world war i 
the nascent state of lithuania was forced to set up its capital 
in kaunas 60 miles away a fact lithuanians have neither forgotten 
nor forgiven 
after poland fell in the early days of world war ii and the 
soviets annexed lithuania vilnius was made capital of the 
lithuanian soviet socialist republic one of the 15 republics 
making up the ussr 
a year later the nazis swept in during a brutal occupation 
they killed nearly all of the citys jews the partisan polish home 
army drove out the germans in 1944 but then came soviet commissars 
who arrested the poles in turn 
after the war vilnius damaged old town was lovingly repaired 
including the 400yearold vilnius university where the polish 
faculty was deported to poland and replaced by russian professors 
at ostra brama the pointed gate in the last remaining segment 
of the old city wall polish pilgrims come again to pray before the 
painting of our lady of ostra brama which used to rank with our 
lady of czestochowa as the most revered of polish icons 
a synagogue also remains and bakeries still sell round rings 
very much like bagels in addition to bricklike loaves of black 
bread a local specialty 
the mixture of cultures is what gives vilnius its special charm 
says a lithuanianspeaking resident of russian polish and jewish 
descent who asked that her name not be used 
vilnius was always so she said it has always been a 
crossing of nations there were four nations living here poles 
lithuanians russians and jews they lived here peacefully 
because of this vilnius has this open tolerant character 
</TEXT>
