<TEXT>
when the white government 
established black homelands in the 1960s it saw them as the 
perfection of segregation and the ultimate answer to south africas 
racial conflict 
now those homelands long ignored and usually docile are 
turning on their creators some are becoming a force in the 
struggle against apartheid south africas official policy of 
segregation by race 
military leaders who seized power sunday in the ciskei homeland 
left no doubt of their loyalties they were flanked at their first 
news conference by officials of the african national congress the 
main black group fighting white domination 
the coup ousted president lennox sebe 63 one of several 
authoritarian leaders of homelands who have worked closely with 
south african security forces and suppressed antiapartheid 
activists 
homeland leaders of sebes generation face increasing pressure 
from restless young activists who see the homelands as an attempt 
to restrict blacks to the most isolated and underdeveloped parts of 
the country 
south africa spends hundreds of millions of dollars annually to 
support the homelands which have little industry or arable land 
brig gen oupa gqozo 37 who led the ciskei coup said he 
wants the homeland to relinquish its nominal independence and 
return to south africa 
the homelands are falling apart unable to contain the 
accelerating rate of political change the antiapartheid 
newspaper weekly mail said in an editorial 
rising expectations for reincorporation in south africa and 
longrunning resentment against poverty have led to strikes 
demonstrations and political violence 
south africa has 10 black homelands and has declared four of 
them independent since 1976 including siskei their independence 
is not recognized abroad 
about half of south africas 28 million blacks live in the 
homelands which are scattered across the eastern half of the 
country and were established when hendrik verwoerd led south africa 
as prime minister in the 1960s 
verwoerd sought to make all blacks citizens of the homelands 
giving them local autonomy and leaving whites in control of the 
national economy and government 
the rule of older conservative tribal chiefs in the homelands 
began to falter in 1987 when gen bantu holomisa then 32 seized 
power in transkei 
holomisa made overtures to antiapartheid groups and favors a 
referendum on whether transkei should relinquish independence and 
return to south africa 
he recently helped organize a huge rally for walter sisulu and 
other leaders of the african national congress which rejects the 
homelands and praised holomisa as an antiapartheid ally 
leaders of the lebowa and kwangane homelands also have expressed 
support for the anc 
since holomisa began making changes in transkei rebellion has 
increased in other homelands 
among recent developments 
dissident army officers in bophuthatswana held president lucas 
mangope hostage in february 1988 until the south african military 
intervened and restored him to power 
in the past month unrest has has cost six lives and injured 
dozens of people mangope rejects calls to return the territory to 
south africa and declared we will be an independent state 100 
years from now 
hudson ntsanwisi chief minister of gazankulu was not seen in 
public for several days during recent violence in which at least 10 
people were killed students workers and bureaucrats have 
conducted strikes or demonstrations in recent weeks 
civil servants have been striking in venda and at least 18 
people were reported killed several in confrontations with 
authorities 
in kwazulu supporters of mangosuthu buthelezi the chief 
minister are involved in a 4yearold power struggle with 
antiapartheid groups aligned with the anc 
buthelezi sees the homelands as a step on the path to black 
majority rule he opposes apartheid but parts with the anc over 
its support for guerrilla warfare sanctions boycotts and other 
confrontational measures 
south africa sent security forces into ciskei to stop looting 
but did not indicate monday that it planned to restore sebe who 
was accused of widespread corruption the south africans have not 
tried to intervene on behalf of other homeland leaders threatened 
by unrest 
president fw de klerk has not renounced any aspect of the 
homeland system or taken a position on returning the areas to south 
africa he has said however that the homelands will be welcome to 
take part in negotiations on a new south african constitution 
</TEXT>
