<TEXT>
the us tax court has upheld an irs order 
denying a tax exemption to a south carolina private school on 
grounds it discriminates against blacks 
the absence of either a single black student in the school or 
a plausible explanation of inability to attract black students 
permits an inference of discrimination particularly in view of 
the schools history the court held 
the decision made public monday means that contributions to 
calhoun academy in st matthews sc are not deductible 
chief judge arthur l nims iii held that although calhoun had 
adopted a racially nondiscriminatory policy the school had failed 
to operate under that policy 
we cannot conclude that nondiscrimination in operations 
is more likely than discrimination nims wrote for the court 
calhoun organized as a notforprofit corporation dec 30 
1969 offers classes for grades kindergarten through 12 the school 
has never had a black pupil or teacher two black parents requested 
and were given application forms for enrollment in 198485 but a 
black teacher has never applied for employment 
since 1982 at least one pupil of oriental background has been 
enrolled in calhoun the only nonwhite teacher a 
japaneseamerican was hired in 1983 court records showed 
the school amended its charter in 1985 and began advertising 
that it did not discriminate it applied to the internal revenue 
service for a tax exemption in 1986 
the irs denied the exemption citing the fact that calhoun was 
formed at a time of enforced desegregation in area public schools 
its total lack of black pupils despite blacks being a majority in 
calhoun county and its failure to announce a policy of 
nondiscrimination until 1985 
at a later meeting the irs suggested that calhoun improve its 
contacts with the black community and offer reduced tuition for 
black pupils a director of the school rejected the reducedtuition 
suggestion saying it would result in unequal treatment on the 
basis of race 
in siding with the irs the tax court cited a 1983 case in which 
the supreme court had stripped a tax exemption from bob jones 
university after finding that it discriminated on the basis of race 
the supreme court held that racially discriminatory schools 
violate fundamental public policy and cannot be viewed as 
conferring a benefit on the public 
from the record before us nims wrote it appears that 
white students and their parents gravitate to petitioner calhoun 
at least in part because of a historical absence of black students 
petitioner admits that the local public schools are superior in 
material respects yet considerably less expensive 
petitioners survival would thus depend to some extent on 
perpetuating its history the court ruled adding that such 
discrimination would clearly preclude a federal tax exemption 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

