a prosecution witness against joseph 
hazelwood clashed angrily today with a defense attorney who 
suggested the witness had been coached to give opinions damaging to 
the skipper of the exxon valdez 
william milwee jr an expert in salvaging grounded vessels 
shouted they didnt tell me to say anything as attorney 
michael chalos attacked his testimony 
milwee has said that hazelwood was reckless in his maneuvering 
of the grounded tanker after it rammed a jagged reef he has said 
hazelwood risked capsizing the ship by trying to run it off the 
reef 
chalos produced a letter from prosecutors to milwee which 
suggested facts supporting those opinions the letter was dated 
before milwee wrote his report in the case but milwee said he 
formed his opinion independently 
the interrogation came as the prosecution prepared to close its 
case against hazelwood defense lawyers were marshalling expert 
witnesses to show the nations worst oil spill was an accident not 
a crime 
any captain that was ever involved in a grounding or a 
collision could be in the defendants chair if a maritime accident 
were a crime said defense attorney michael chalos 
chalos who said hazelwood was feeling better after a bout with 
the flu said the defense planned to call about 10 witnesses the 
prosecution was expected to rest today or tuesday 
defense witnesses will range from experts in matters of the sea 
to fact witnesses who saw hazelwood on the day his ship 
grounded they will seek to show that his actions do not support 
felony and misdemeanor charges 
these are not criminal acts the lawyer said in an interview 
sunday this is a maritime accident 
chalos said an expert in computer simulations will show jurors 
conclusively that the exxon valdez voyage would have ended safely 
if crew members followed the skippers orders for navigating 
through a narrow passage into prince william sound 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny was absent from the ships 
bridge when the 987foot tanker went aground on jagged bligh reef 
last march 24 the prosecution claims he was reckless and has 
charged him with a felony criminal mischief and three 
misdemeanors reckless endangerment operating a vessel while 
intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil 
he could receive up to 7 years in prison and 61000 in fines 
the three issues which the prosecution has raised and which the 
defense must address are hazelwoods alleged intoxication his 
departure from the bridge 10 minutes before the accident and his 
alleged recklessness in trying to move the tanker off the reef 
after the grounding 
the exxon valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil into 
the clear waters of prince william sound killing thousands of 
birds fish and other wildlife and coating hundreds of miles of 
rocky shore with black goo 
chalos sees the alcohol issue as the keystone of the 
prosecutions case and suggests there is no conclusive proof 
hazelwood was intoxicated if they cant prove intoxication its 
a very flimsy case he said 
an expert in alcohol toxicology was expected to be the 
prosecutions climactic final witness and the defense will answer 
with its own expert interpreting hazelwoods blood alcohol reading 
of 061 in a test 10 hours after the grounding 
does this indicate alcohol consumed hours before the ship sailed 
or possible drinking after the ship grounded no one has said and 
not a single witness has described hazelwood as appearing drunk 
the charge of recklessness hinges on hazelwoods actions after 
the grounding 
prosecution witnesses have accused hazelwood of recklessly 
risking his ship and the lives of crew members by trying to run the 
tanker off the reef the defense insists he never tried to get off 
the reef and said exxons salvage master will support that point in 
testimony 
but even if hazelwood did try to move the tanker the defense 
says it would never have budged the prosecutions own experts 
have said conclusively that it couldnt move said defense 
attorney thomas russo 
to find hazelwood guilty of recklnessness russo said the jury 
must believe there was a substantial risk the skipper ignored 
there was no risk because it couldnt move russo said if 
you cant commit the crime there is no crime 
of course only one witness can say exactly what the captain had 
in mind on the fateful night and that is the captain will he 
testify 
we havent decided that yet said russo and we wont 
decide it until the very end 
