<TEXT>
the supreme court slammed shut the federal 
courthouse door monday to fresh appeals by many convicted 
criminals including death row inmates 
in two 54 rulings the court generally barred defendants from 
using new constitutional rulings to attack state court convictions 
after exhausting initial rounds of appeals 
the justices upheld a south carolina death row prisoners 
conviction and reinstated the death sentence of a convicted 
oklahoma murderer 
the courts four dissenters and the american civil liberties 
union denounced the rulings 
the aclu in a statement signed by three officials said the 
court has sent a clear signal that it will turn away and allow 
people to be executed in plain violation of the bill of rights 
in the south carolina case the court upheld the conviction of 
horace butler sentenced to die for the 1980 murder of pamela lane 
a clerk at a charlestonarea convenience store 
the court refused to apply retroactively to butlers case a 1988 
ruling that limits police questioning the 1988 decision said 
police may not question a suspect about a crime the one for which 
he was arrested or any other once he asks for a lawyer 
the 1988 ruling was foreshadowed by a 1981 decision banning a 
second round of police questions about the crime for which a 
suspect was arrested 
butler was in jail on a relatively minor charge and had obtained 
a lawyers representation after refusing to talk to police police 
later questioned him about an unrelated murder and butler 
confessed 
butler asked a federal judge to throw out his murder conviction 
on grounds that under the supreme courts 1988 ruling his rights 
were violated by unlawful police interrogation 
chief justice william h rehnquist writing for the court said 
it was too late for the 1988 ruling to be of any help to butler 
prisoners cannot rely on new high court rulings to overturn 
their convictions as long as the state appeals courts that upheld 
the convictions reasonably interpreted thencurrent constitutional 
rulings rehnquist said 
he was joined by justices byron r white sandra day oconnor 
antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
in a dissenting opinion justice william j brennan said the 
decision strips state prisoners of virtually any meaningful 
federal review of the constitutionality of their incarceration 
after today despite constitutional defects in the state 
processes leading to their conviction or sentencing state 
prisoners will languish in jail and others like butler will die 
because state courts were reasonable even though wrong brennan 
said 
he said that with mondays ruling the court has finally 
succeeded in its thinly veiled crusade to eviscerate federal laws 
aimed at protecting criminal defendants rights 
brennan was joined by justices thurgood marshall harry a 
blackmun and john paul stevens 
in the oklahoma case the same five majority justices ruled that 
robyn leroy parks is barred from contending that a jury wrongly was 
told to ignore sympathy before it sentenced him to death 
but kennedy wrote that parks was barred from raising that 
argument after exhausting his direct appeals in state courts 
parks was convicted of the 1977 killing of abdullah ibrahim a 
gas station attendant in oklahoma city at parks sentencing trial 
the judge told jurors you must avoid any influence of sympathy 
sentiment passion prejudice or other arbitrary factor when 
imposing sentence 
the justices overturned a ruling by the 10th us circuit court 
of appeals that said the judges instruction undermined the jurys 
consideration of mitigating evidence the appeals court had 
said parks should be resentenced 
