first of its kind and encouraged other naacp chapters to 
negotiate similar agreements 
the baltimorebased national association for the advancement of 
colored people had planned to boycott the mall if no agreement was 
reached gibson said 
george forbes an attorney for mall owner jacobs visconi and 
jacobs of cleveland said the agreement was reached in a spirit 
of cooperation but is not legally binding 
the columbia mall does not it has not and it will not 
discriminate as regards to race creed or color said forbes a 
longtime member of the naacp there seemed to be an indication 
that we have done that and i consistently said that we have not 
and anyone at the mall found to be involved with that would be 
immediately dismissed 
the agreement negotiated over the last month by naacp and mall 
officials calls for hiring and promoting more blacks by mall 
management and encouraging stores to do the same and for using 
more black contractors and suppliers 
however the pact does not specify the number of jobs or work 
contracts the mall will give to blacks 
the malls owners also offered to sponsor a jobs fair create an 
employment center advertise in the black media provide 
sensitivity training for employees and work with the naacp to 
closely monitor the malls relationship with the black community 
informal studies show blacks comprise 30 percent to 40 percent 
of the malls 150000 weekly customers gibson said 
about a month ago the mall discontinued its practice of 
detaining black youths under a 1960s antitrespassing law designed 
to maintain segregation jacobs said 
