<DOCNO> AP900305-0166 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a witness testified monday that the 
exxon valdez would have capsized if skipper joseph hazelwood could 
have gotten it off a reef but the judge said the statement may be 
irrelevant 
in a tentative opinion following heated legal argument superior 
court judge karl johnstone said he may instruct jurors that the 
tanker was immovable so hazelwood could not have risked capsizing 
it even if he tried to move it 
johnstone said testimony so far convinced him that the ship was 
hard aground on the reef and could not be moved off by its own 
power 
the judge however refused a defense request to strike the 
testimony of william vorus a professor of naval architecture who 
said the ship was unbalanced after losing oil from some of its 
tanks and would have capsized if it got off the reef 
the judge stressed that he had not made a final ruling on the 
issue and thus continued to allow testimony by vorus about what 
would have happened if the exxon valdez was freed from the reef 
the march 24 grounding of the exxon valdez on bligh reef caused 
the nations worst oil spill spewing nearly 11 million gallons of 
alaska crude oil that devastated the rich population of wildlife in 
prince william sound 
the judge accepted a prosecution argument that hazelwoods 
apparent efforts to move the ship could be used to show that his 
judgment was impaired by alcohol 
the alaska statute covering criminal mischief includes an 
additional definition of recklessness saying that a person who is 
intoxicated and thus unaware of a risk may be considered reckless 
with respect to that risk 
in a brief filed with the judge shortly before mondays session 
the defense argued hazelwood could not have disregarded a risk 
which didnt exist 
the state must show that he actually knew of the risk that it 
was a substantial and unjustifiable one and that he consciously 
disregarded it defense attorney dick madson said in the document 
in addition to the charge of criminal mischief hazelwood is 
charged with three misdemeanors reckless endangerment operating a 
vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil 
the 43yearold hazelwood of huntington ny faces up to 7 
years in prison and 61000 in fines if convicted on all counts 
the criminal mischief charge the most serious requires a 
showing that hazelwood risked damage to someone elses property 
valued at more than 100000 
johnstone said the prosecutor specified before trial that the 
property in question was the shoreline of alaska and the wildlife 
of prince william sound 
but during the legal arguments assistant district attorney 
brent cole said he might change that if necessary to claim that 
hazelwood risked damage to his ship by trying to get it off the 
reef 
the judge did not immediately say whether he would permit such a 
change in strategy at this point 
vorus a professor at the university of michigan in ann arbor 
explained how the ship was unbalanced when holes punched in the 
hull allowed sea water to replace the oil which weighed less than 
the water 
asked for his expert opinion vorus responded if it had 
gotten off the reef our analysis shows it would have capsized 
and sunk 
prior to vorus testimony william milwee jr an expert in 
salvage of grounded ships heatedly denied a defense lawyers 
suggestion that he was coached by the prosecution into his 
conclusion that hazelwood acted recklessly when he tried to 
maneuver the ship after running aground 
i independently reached my opinion milwee said 
</TEXT>
