serious environmental emission was what landed on a dirt road 
its just a tradition said the societys president lewis 
leggett 78 who cant remember when he joined the group the last 
time anyone called on the society to track a stolen horse was in 
1917 when henry ford was busy transforming the nations stables 
into garages 
for woody klose president of the red hook society for the 
apprehension and detention of horse thieves in neighboring dutchess 
county carrying on the group is more than tradition 
its got to be the greatest organization in the world said 
klose a lawyer and county legislator it meets just once a year 
and we havent had a horse theft in years thieves are so terrified 
of us that they leave our horses alone 
in columbia county a mule went on the hoof in the 1930s but it 
came back by itself one year someone stole the hobbyhorse off a 
villagers porch another year a society member stole the group 
presidents old gray horse as a joke the prankster wasnt hanged 
or even horsewhipped 
about 10 years ago a couple of horses were stolen from a local 
breeding farm but police didnt call on the volunteer posse 
i think they figured the troopers could do a better job 
said society secretary ralph duck 
yet the group still has nearly 200 members who gather once a 
year to meet with old friends they otherwise wouldnt see said 
duck 79 who joined about 50 years ago 
the group began when eastern new york was still on the frontier 
and horse thieves ran unbridled among the farming towns hugging the 
hudson river horses were practically part of the family doubling 
as transportation and as plow power 
you could probably get away with stealing a mans wife easier 
than stealing a mans horse leggett said if you lost your 
horse you lost your heart 
the society still has the noose used to hang horse thieves but 
members dont know when if ever it was used 
ive always had the feeling they didnt hang them around here 
like they did in the wild west duck said 
similarly the minutes of the red hook society are terrific 
about writing down who didnt show up at the meetings but they 
dont say anything about catching horse thieves klose said 
i cant find any report of a member ever having done 
anything he said 
a feeling of continuity keeps the 65 members of the red hook 
society founded in 1796 crowding around the trough for their 
roast beef dinner on the first tuesday of every october klose said 
we still live in what we like to think of as a semirural 
area he said it makes you feel good because you can go back 
to minutes from seven or eight generations ago and find the same 
names of people attending our meetings today 
unable to afford fulltime posses farming villages formed 
societies like todays volunteer fire departments to trail 
horse thieves 
each year societies elected a group of riders who would be 
called in when a horse was stolen the columbia county society paid 
its riders 2 a day while they were on the trail red hook riders 
earned more money the farther they rode they got a bonus if they 
trailed a horse thief out of dutchess county and brought the bandit 
back home klose said 
the societies also acted as insurers paying farm families the 
money to replace stolen horses 
as automobiles and tractors replaced horses in the early 1900s 
most horse theft societies folded 
on todays thoroughbred ranches there are few worries about 
stolen horse flesh its tough to launder a stud horse whose value 
depends on careful documentation of its parentage 
if you wanted to take a stolen horse to outer mongolia you 
could probably get away with it said mary midkiff of the 
american horse council in washington dc 
while horses dont vanish from new york farms anymore horse 
