<TEXT>
john steinbeck always turned down requests to 
adapt for the stage the grapes of wrath his epic novel about 
dust bowl okies and their migration to the promised land of 
california 
he loved the film version starring henry fonda which was 
written by nunnally johnson and directed by john ford all three of 
them his good friends but he didnt want to see the story as a 
play 
i think john wondered if it would be visual in a theater 
says elaine steinbeck the writers third wife and most ardent fan 
after he died in 1968 she continued to reject proposals for a 
play except for a local production at actors theater of louisville 
in the early 1980s 
but the minute steppenwolf asked me i said yes adds 
steinbecks widow referring to the chicago theater company that 
has made a name for itself all over the world with its highly 
kinetic freewheeling productions 
i knew their reputation and had seen orphans in london and 
balm in gilead in new york they were professional imaginative 
exciting and had sent their actors directors and plays out into 
the theatrical mainstream 
i also knew that the 50th anniversary of the publication of 
the grapes of wrath was going to come up last april the book 
was first published in april 1939 and i felt wouldnt that be a 
wonderful time for somebody to do the play 
the steppenwolf version adapted and directed by frank galati 
opened in chicago in september 1988 and was done later in la jolla 
calif and at the royal national theater in london now it has 
made the trek to broadway where it has found a house at the cort 
theater 
the book the story of the joad family and their journey 
westward during the great depression is known everywhere in the 
united states alone in every one of those 50 years from 1939 to 
1989 it has never sold fewer than 100000 copies it has been 
published in 40 languages 
whenever anybody would say whats your favorite novel john 
would say the one ive just finished but i think he had taste 
enough to know that the grapes of wrath was his big book says 
mrs steinbeck in a soft texas twang not erased by her more than 
50 years in new york 
mrs steinbeck one of broadways first female stage managers 
worked on such shows as the original oklahoma and othello 
with paul robeson she first met her future husband in 1949 when he 
was collaborating with elia kazan on the movie viva zapata and 
doing research for a novel that eventually became east of eden 
he was recently divorced and told me im very disillusioned 
and very unhappy he had two young boys and his wife divorced him 
and he said i dont want to ever love another woman or ever write 
another book well look what happened 
the couple was married in 1950 they kept homes in new york and 
in sag harbor on long island but traveled a lot particularly to 
london and italy they made up for the time he was too poor to 
travel 
i once asked him when f scott fitzgerald and ernest 
hemingway and all those other writers were going to paris why 
didnt you go he said i didnt have the price of a ticket but 
im glad i didnt because i stayed home and wrote about my own 
people 
fans of the film version of the grapes of wrath will find a 
different emphasis in the play one that is much truer to the book 
mrs steinbeck says 
the movie was a star vehicle for henry fonda who played tom 
joad it really ends when tom leaves she says 
in the book the central figure all the way through is ma 
joad they all leave her for one reason or another even tom and 
she says we are the people we must prevail we must go on i 
feel thats what frank galati was going for in the play 
john didnt write many womens parts as a matter of fact 
critics used to say steinbeck writes better men than women he 
would always look at me and say how about ma joad 
during their years together steinbeck would write every day in 
longhand usually after sharpening threedozen pencils his widow 
recalls that was stalling she says if he was working on a 
long book steinbeck would keep regular hours but he would start 
the morning writing letters 
john always said writing letters was like a pitcher warming 
up he would write letters before he would write his work or when 
we traveled he wrote travel pieces just things that interested 
him not things that would live forever he kept a journal for 
every book 
when she first met him one of the first things they did was to 
drive to salinas calif where he was born to see the little room 
on the top floor of the house where he first started writing i 
cant remember a time when i didnt write he told her as he 
showed her the building 
steinbeck did a lot of research on the grapes of wrath he 
wrote a series of pieces called the harvest gypsies for a 
nowdefunct san francisco newspaper and then realized it was a 
book not newspaper articles 
he loved to think of himself as a journalist mrs steinbeck 
says i dont think he was accurate enough to be a journalist he 
always embroidered a bit hed always throw a little bit extra in 
when john won the nobel prize he said i dont know whether 
i deserve it or not but i certainly am glad i got it she 
recalls 
i dont think that john ever got fancy when he became 
successful he didnt start writing a different kind of story he 
still wrote about the people he knew john cared about the people 
he talked the same way to great french writers at the academy 
francaise as he did to the fishermen at sag harbor he never talked 
down to anybody 
</TEXT>
