estimates military spending by the 16 nato members will decline 27 
percent this year from about 450 billion he said it was off 11 
percent last year adjusted for inflation 
the united states which accounts for about twothirds of the 
total probably will reduce spending by 3 percent this year and 
european expenditures could decline slightly more than 2 percent 
sen said 
it will be difficult for defense ministers to ask for more 
in the new political climate sen predicted 
officials say few members will meet natos guideline of a 3 
percent growth in spending this year the target has been in effect 
since the 1970s and the alliances defense ministers probably will 
abolish it soon 
some countries may keep spending up because of regional 
problems greece and turkey for instance were enemies long before 
they were nato allies 
greece has exceeded the united states in the share of its 
economic output devoted to defense last year it spent 6 percent 
of its gross national product on the military the highest in nato 
and greater than the 55 percent spent by the americans according 
to alliance estimates 
turkey one of only two nato members bordering the soviet union 
also worries about neighbors syria iraq and iran its military 
now undergoing modernization gets about a onequarter of the 
budget 
norway the other nato nation with a soviet frontier has 
drafted plans to increase military expenditures by 25 percent this 
year 
analysts say west germany will be under great pressure to cut 
defense spending so its powerful economy can help east germany 
bonn talks of reducing its army from 480000 to 400000 in the 
1990s and has suspended a plan to increase the conscription term 
from 15 months to 18 
military hardware is a major target of budget cutters because of 
negotiations in vienna austria on reducing conventional forces in 
europe which are expected to produce an agreement this year 
countries will for the first time be looking at actually 
reducing the numbers of equipment they require its a new 
environment for force planners said simon lunn deputy 
secretarygeneral of the north atlantic assembly made up of 
legislators from nato nations 
arms negotiators for example want to limit each side to 20000 
main battle tanks long the dominant weapon in land combat 
for the thinnedout battlefield of the future governments 
may place more emphasis on sophisticated mobile weapons analysts 
say 
nato members have begun pulling out of costly joint arms 
programs set up years ago to produce modern weapons that could be 
shared 
today as defense budgets shrink we see cooperative programs 
running into severe difficulties william h taft iv the us 
ambassador to nato said in a recent speech 
a senior alliance official who agreed to discuss the situation 
only if granted anonymity said were in this indecisive period 
now where to rush in to create new programs is probably not 
wise thats why all these countries are sort of retrenching on 
the programs 
an eightnation plan to develop the warship of the 1990s has 
collapsed britain france and italy withdrew last fall followed 
in quick succession by west germany spain and the netherlands 
leaving only canada and the united states 
britain and the united states have turned their backs on plans 
to build a weapon that fighter planes could fire from a distance 
without flying over enemy territory france and canada got out 
earlier 
spain italy and west germany are considering whether to 
continue but one official said on condition of anonymity the 
investment for research and development would be so significant 
that its not likely they will have the strength to carry it 
themselves 
the united states dropped out of an eightnation program to 
develop special 155mm ammunition to seek out enemy armor a few 
years ago it persuaded west germany to stay in officials said 
interest also is waning in a project to develop a family of 
airtoair missiles of short and medium range west germany said 
last year it no longer would participate in building the 
shortrange version leaving britain canada and norway 
spain italy britain and west germany are in the european 
fighter aircraft project but continued german participation is in 
question 
another major expense is stationing soldiers in west germany 
the front line of the western alliance 
as part of a conventional arms treaty the soviet union and the 
united states plan to reduce their troop strength in central europe 
to 195000 soldiers each with the united states allowed 30000 
more on natos flanks 
that means the soviets would remove 370000 soldiers and the 
united states would withdraw 80000 
reductions in arms should allow other nato members to call home 
the soldiers who operate those weapons 
