<TEXT>
the figures on his order pad are 
harder to make out these days his hearing aids can turn 
conversations into shouting matches and he doesnt go anywhere 
without a cane 
but at 90 charlie tucker is still doing what he does best 
peddling mops and dusters can openers and furniture polish just 
about anything you might need 
and if he doesnt get around quite as good as he used to he 
still knows how to move fuller brushes 
your wife might be able to use this he says opening a box 
in his dining room and pulling out a mop head that looks kind of 
like raggedy ann as a blonde 
its regularly 5 but weve got it on special for just 399 
oh youre not married tucker hardly misses a beat well how 
about your mom 
tucker has been selling household products for fuller brush for 
59 years and if you live in this part of the country hes 
probably tried to entice you with a free spatula or vegetable brush 
i just love sales work i reckon says tucker a tidy 
compact man whose perfect white hair may be a byproduct of decades 
of making a good first impression 
mrs eugene collins 61 of chattanooga has known tucker since 
she was a teenager and figures shes probably bought about every 
product fuller has ever made 
im still using them i love them and i think mr tucker has 
been a part of that because he is so knowledgeable and tells you 
how to do it and how to use them 
tucker got his start at age 12 selling dynamite and doing odd 
jobs at a company store in the virginia coal fields after world 
war i he hawked newspapers on trains then worked as a buyer of 
piece goods and womens readytowear garments 
but in 1931 his employer went out of business and tucker found 
himself in the great depression with a wife and children but no job 
so he answered an ad for fuller brush and went to work in 
elizabethton selling 150 worth of goods his first week within a 
few weeks that was his daily total earning him the 
congratulations of company founder alfred c fuller and a promotion 
to branch manager in memphis 
he took a similar job in chattanooga in 1934 managing as many 
as 35 salesmen until fuller brush was sold in the 1960s to 
consolidated foods inc of chicago 
the new owners decided to eliminate the district offices and 
tucker decided to return to the sidewalks 
i was back where i started he said i was too old to go 
out and hunt a new job but i figured i could sell fuller brushes 
over the last 20 years tucker has been a familiar figure on 
chattanooga streets often using a mop handle to prop open the 
trunk of his portable warehouse a 1968 plymouth fury 
hes found himself thrust into roles of marriage counselor and 
baby sitter and hes had a door slammed in his face so hard the 
glass shattered 
ive been insulted and everything else but i put my high 
feelings in the closet and lock the door because i would have had 
them hurt if id taken everything seriously he said 
but tucker took his coworkers seriously 
jim clayton 72 worked for fuller brush for 47 years one day 
he said he and tucker were in dayton tenn and tucker told him 
to go to bryan college saying the maintenance department probably 
needed a dozen brooms 
well i walked to the boiler room and the guy said hello 
and i said im the fuller brush man and he said bring me a 
dozen brooms now if id been charlie tucker id have said you 
catch these customers down here and ill go tend to that college 
no use kidding myself but thats just the kind of guy charlie 
tucker always was 
when tucker went to work in 1931 the company offered about a 
dozen items now there are 400 products and 13000 sales 
representatives all of whom still work strictly on commission 
its the kind of challenge tucker likes 
were selling one day and im on this porch and hes on the 
porch next door clayton said and this lady comes to the door 
and she dont want to buy and he said well i understand but 
when you see your neighbors using our specials i want to remember 
you had a chance to turn it down ill just step in and show it to 
you and he stepped in and then stepped out in about three minutes 
with a nice order 
ive never yet found a door that id hesitate to knock on 
whether its the governors or whoevers tucker said with a 
grin im no highpressure salesman but maybe ill try to create 
a desire sufficient to overcome your resistance 
these days tucker relies mostly on telephone sales by his wife 
neoma and on repeat customers who pick up their goods at his home 
in north chattanooga 
he hasnt driven since last summer when he underwent 
complicated heart and kidney surgery but after nearly 60 years 
its hard to kick the habit 
hes feeling better and his eyes light up at the mention of 
spring 
if i get anywhere back to normal ill be back knocking on 
doors 
