<DOCNO> AP900305-0211 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
paul j lochray is an attorney and expert in 
estate planning for the denverbased college for financial 
planning 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
estate planning and postmortem planning make most 
people squirm 
many of us avoid making a will or setting a plan for disposition 
of assets upon our death for two simple reasons we are uneasy with 
the thought that we will die and we feel that our estates are too 
small to justify the time and expense involved in preparing a will 
regardless of the size of your estate or your philosophy on 
death estate planning and postmortem planning involve everything 
you have worked for during your life and ensure that your wishes 
will be followed should you become incapacitated or die 
there are five important reasons for making a will you can 
choose your donees minimize taxes appoint a guardian name an 
executor and establish a domicile 
in the absence of a will up to half a married persons property 
usually will be distributed to the surviving spouse with the 
remainder passing to the deceaseds children only if the deceased 
had adopted the spouses children from a previous marriage would 
those children be included in the distribution of property 
even though this distribution of property may not be consistent 
with your wishes you have no recourse by failing to prepare a 
will you have abdicated the right to select your beneficiaries 
and what and how much each beneficiary is to receive 
a properly prepared will can help to alleviate any tax liability 
that might be levied against your estate taxable estates valued at 
less than 600000 are exempt from federal estate tax but hidden 
resources life insurance policies naming the decedent as the 
insured or qualified retirement plan benefits and iras can swell 
the estates value oftentimes making it subject to federal estate 
taxation trusts and other techniques available through your will 
can lessen this tax burden 
if you have children perhaps your greatest concern is who would 
take care of them if both you and your spouse died a will can be 
used to name a guardian courts generally will accommodate the 
wishes of the parents in cases where a guardian is named 
without a will you have no say in who carries out the 
administration of your estate if no will exists the court will 
appoint an administrator and the court could appoint a creditor 
they sometimes qualify for this position which would not 
necessarily be in the best interests of your estate by naming an 
executor you can ensure that a trustworthy person of your choosing 
will handle the administration of your estate 
finally for tax and other reasons you may want to establish a 
particular state as your state of domicile or legal residence for 
example if you have moved frequently or have homes in more than 
one state each state could claim you as a resident and subject the 
estate to multiple probate proceedings and overlapping claims to 
state death or inheritance taxes to minimize that risk indicate 
clearly in your will which state you claim as domicile 
experts agree that many people fail to recognize the importance 
of a will a person who dies intestate without a will can 
leave many problems for loved ones and greatly reduce the chances 
that undocumented intentions will be carried out the solution for 
everyone no matter the size of the estate is to have a will 
prepared now and alleviate some of the uncertainties and problems 
that could arise later 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
