channel one a news show with advertisements 
aimed at teenagers made its national debut in an estimated 14000 
classrooms today with paid pitches for two kinds of snack foods and 
a razor 
the show was airing in about 400 schools across the country the 
producers said even as critics continued to argue that its daily 
regimen of commercials is out of place in the classroom 
the advertisers on the first day of the program were mampms candy 
from mampm mars cheetos snacks from fritolay inc and the sensor 
razor from gillette co 
the program which lasts 12 minutes with two minutes allocated 
for advertising also included an antidrug public service 
commercial 
the show is the most ambitious and controversial project yet 
from whittle communications a knoxville tennbased company 
headed by chairman christopher whittle that creates magazines and 
other media used by advertisers to reach narrowly defined audiences 
a typical show begins with two young anchors giving the top 
stories of the day followed by a chapter in a fivepart series 
each week a pop quiz and some interesting facts and a closing 
story 
the first weeks featured series deals with the fall of the 
berlin wall and how events in eastern europe have affected teens 
there 
architects of the channel one program say it should produce 
handsome educational dividends for students and educators as well 
as potentially lucrative financial rewards for the company 
producing it 
but critics say the commercials represent an unwarranted 
intrusion on a captive audience of students who are required by law 
to be in school 
officials in the states of new york and california have 
prohibited public schools in those states from carrying the program 
because of the commercials a state board of education ban on 
channel one in north carolina was overturned friday by a state 
court judge freeing schools there to use the system 
several national education groups are opposing channel one and 
are backing use of a daily commercialfree news show for teens that 
the cable giant turner broadcasting system inc began running last 
august on its cable news network 
but whittle said commercials are an essential element of the 
channel one system because revenue from the 150000 charge for 
each 30second ad pays for the 150 million in video equipment 
loaned to schools that show the program and the 90 million in 
operational expenses needed to produce it 
whittle said his surveys show few if any students are getting a 
chance to watch the turner adfree news program in school because 
there are few tv sets available in most schools 
ed winter the executive overseeing the channel one project 
said more than 2700 schools in 34 states have signed threeyear 
contracts to show the program to their students every school day 
he said six of every 10 schools approached have agreed to sign 
four hundred of these schools with 300000 students have been 
equipped with the dozens of tv sets a satellite dish and video 
recorders needed to record the show which is transmitted 
automatically overnight by satellite 
the company is signing schools to the system at the rate of more 
than 100 a week and hopes to have 1000 participating by the end 
of march and 7000 to 8000 schools with 6 million students by next 
march 
the channel one program was tested last year for seven weeks in 
six schools and whittle said it boosted student awareness of 
current events and can be a powerful educational tool 
