<TEXT>
it was hardly a typical deal for frank lorenzo 
head of an airline empire takeover strategist and consummate 
dealmaker 
this time the wily chairman of texas air corp got burned 
his adversary wasnt the head of a rival airline or one of his 
texas air subordinates or even a union leader it was david i 
shapiro the courtappointed bankruptcy examiner for eastern 
airlines a texas air subsidiary 
lorenzo and his associates believed they had a deal with shapiro 
on eastern and that the washington attorney sandbagged them 
according to sources close to the negotiations who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
the dispute wasnt over prices to be paid for assets labor 
concessions or airline routes it was over words powerful words in 
a report by shapiro that claimed texas air had shortchanged 
eastern when it bought the airline and some of its assets 
shapiro had been directed to supervise an investigation of 
eastern and its dealings with texas air and sister carrier 
continental airlines as part of easterns chapter 11 bankruptcy 
proceeding which started last march after pilots flight 
attendants and machinists struck the miamibased airline 
his report filed last thursday in federal bankruptcy court 
concluded that texas air purchased eastern assets at unfairly low 
prices and owed the carrier 285 million to 403 million 
texas air and eastern publicly called his report replete with 
faulty analyses hearsay evidence statements taken out of context 
and misstatements of fact the companies threatened last friday 
to take serious and considered actions to clear their names 
texas air spokesman art kent wouldnt say what form those 
actions might take and declined further comment 
shapiro declined comment today when reached at his law firm in 
washington dc 
there is sufficient evidence to warrant the bringing of 
charges that 12 transactions provided eastern with less than fair 
consideration or reasonably equivalent value the report said 
the court could therefore appropriately authorize litigation 
of these 12 claims 
charges litigation those were words lorenzo and his team 
werent expecting to see in the report according to the sources 
houstonbased texas air had agreed earlier with shapiro to pay 
eastern more than 280 million as a settlement on the condition 
sources said that the report not assign any liability to texas air 
texas air admitted no wrongdoing in the settlement and said it 
agreed to make the payment to eastern only to bolster the airline 
although shapiros report said there were grounds for 
litigation he recommended court approval of the settlement as an 
alternative nevertheless his premise could tarnish texas airs 
image because it implied wrongdoing on the companys part 
shapiro concluded a deal on the settlement with texas air 
officials at around midnight last wednesday he was scheduled to 
submit his report to the court and speak at a hearing on the 
subject the next day 
on thursday morning texas air officials received copies of the 
