wasnt what they were expecting 
some texas air officials initially believed shapiros associates 
at his washington office misunderstood his instructions to them 
when he called around midnight wednesday from new york after 
striking the deal with texas air sources said 
the examiner apparently had two versions of his report prepared 
the sources said after reaching agreement with the company he is 
believed to have told his colleagues to submit to the court the 
version that excluded mention of possible litigation against the 
company someone on shapiros team goofed some insiders believed 
shapiro had two reports written from the getgo said a 
source close to the investigation who described one version as 
heavyhanded and the other as wimpy 
under a later theory shapiros team failed in a frantic effort 
starting late wednesday to revise the report to reflect the 
settlement in time for thursdays hearing according to that 
scenario shapiro asked us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland for 
more time but his request was refused 
the hearing before lifland was scheduled for 2 pm est its 
start was delayed however as shapiro met in a stormy session in 
liflands chambers with attorneys for eastern and texas air 
easterns unions and its major creditors 
they went ballistic said one of those present describing 
the company lawyers behavior the company attorneys accused 
shapiro of breaching their agreement 
after the hearing began and shapiro addressed the court he 
departed from his prepared text at some points in an apparent 
softening of the language saying charges could be brought 
against texas air instead of can be brought as the report 
stated 
the examiner also added several sentences indicating that the 
purpose of his report was to determine if there is sufficient 
evidence to establish claims rather than to make a final finding 
of fact 
he said measures to be taken to protect easterns interests 
could include instead of the original should include 
establishment of a monitoring body under the courts supervision 
that issue opposed by texas air had been one of the major 
sticking points in reaching a settlement sources said 
in his report shapiro continued to reject the unions request 
that eastern be run by an outside trustee 
texas air officials said lorenzo was unavailable to comment on 
the settlement 
a union attorney said the report vindicated the unions 
longstanding claims that texas air had stripped assets from 
eastern if texas air didnt agree with the report it shouldnt 
have signed the settlement he said 
we challenge frank lorenzo to withdraw from the settlement and 
let the issues be tried in court said bruce simon an attorney 
for the pilots union 
