<TEXT>
the supreme court today ruled that a dispute 
between florida and an illinoisbased bank holding company blocked 
by florida from setting up an industrial savings bank has become 
legally irrelevant 
the court unanimously ruled that a 1987 federal law giving 
states specific authority to block such moves by outofstate bank 
holding companies has rendered the dispute moot 
the decision is a victory for florida but a setback for 
continental bank corp 
the court last june agreed to review the case even though bush 
administration lawyers told the justices the 1987 change in federal 
banking law had made the case moot 
writing for the court today justice antonin scalia never 
acknowledged the bush administration advice that initially went 
unheeded 
continental bank in 1981 filed an application with the florida 
department of banking and finance to establish and run an 
industrial savings bank in mami 
the proposed bank would not accept demand deposits or make 
commercial loans making it a socalled nonbank bank that 
fell outside the federal laws definition of banks 
the application was denied and continental bank subsequently 
sued in federal court the suit alleged that floridas action was 
unconstitutional 
scalia said 1987 amendments to the bank holding company act of 
1956 bars bank holding companies from establishing or acquiring a 
bank in another state unless the latter states statutes 
specifically authorize it to do so 
the law thus effectively permits states to prevent 
outofstate holding companies from owning instate banks scalia 
said 
the case is lewis vs continental bank 871956 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

