<DOCNO> AP900305-0232 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in the downtown offices of a powerful 
insurance company the walls in a secondfloor suite are decorated 
with buckets and iron bed keys 
they share a place of honor with antique firefighter helmets and 
with steampowered fire engines and hose reels in the lobby of 
cigna corps headquarters the result is a prestigious corporate 
museum 
these samples of the technology that has kept the company in 
business celebrate the long colorful history of firefighting in 
philadelphia where cigna got its start nearly 200 years ago 
insuring against fire and shipping losses 
cignas business traditions are reflected in the museum 
collection devoted to the otherwise unrelated histories of 
maritime shipping and firefighting models and paintings of sailing 
ships the company once insured are displayed around the corner from 
firemens tools and ceremonial clothing 
over the years as more sophisticated equipment gave 
firefighters better odds against the flames insurance companies 
benefited now it is cignas turn to do the salvaging and preserve 
firefighting relics 
the museum collection contains 9000 pieces says curator 
melissa hough many of the best items are exhibited in the downtown 
philadelphia museum but as much as 85 percent of the collection is 
either on loan to museums around the country or spread around 
cignas 60 corporate offices here and abroad ms hough said 
firefighting traditions in philadelphia go back to the bucket 
brigades of the early colonial times the nations first volunteer 
fire company was founded here in 1736 and the first fire insurance 
company ben franklins contributionship started 16 years later 
in the 19th century the firehouse was a center of male 
camaraderie and competition with rivalries played out fighting 
fires 
one museum painting shows a race between horsedrawn fire 
engines of rival companies each trying to be the first to a fire 
another shows several fire companies at an 1850 contest to see 
whose hoses could squirt water the highest 
the competition between volunteer fire companies ms hough 
said eventually became a problem as firemen became just plain 
rowdy they called false alarms to sabotage other companies and 
cut their rivals hoses ms hough said the problem peaked right 
after the civil war and in 1871 the city stepped in and 
established a professional fire department 
many firefighting buffs visit cignas museum in many 
pennsylvania communities volunteer fire companies remain part of 
the social fabric as they once were in philadelphia 
hough said school children come on class trips and one of their 
favorite games is to guess the use of some of the oddlooking tools 
displayed in the museum 
they play with wooden rattles once used by watchmen to rouse 
neighbors in the event of a fire and learn that a strangelooking 
piece of iron is a bed key actually a critical firefighting tool 
firemen carried bed keys so they could quickly disassemble beds 
and carry them out of burning homes beds were among the most 
expensive pieces of furniture and salvaging them was important to 
homeowners as well as to their insurance companies 
in 1794 the insurance company of north america a predecessor 
of cigna was the first to offer fire insurance on the contents of 
a building 
cigna the eighthlargest insurance company in the world had 
revenue of 17 billion in 1988 the last year for which complete 
figures are available 
the portion of company business now devoted to fire insurance is 
difficult to calculate said cigna spokesman james ely because 
fire insurance is typically part of a package including theft and 
liability insurance about 20 percent of cignas revenues are from 
such commercial packages he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note the museum located at 16th and arch streets in 
philadelphia is open mondayfriday 9 am5 pm admission is 
free 
</TEXT>
