<TEXT>
every time florida shivers brazil tightens 
its grip on the us orange juice market 
the south american giant again is shipping millions of gallons 
of juice to the united states at premium prices in the wake of the 
third major freeze in floridas citrus groves in six years 
the flood from a competitor is a mixed blessing florida 
processors may take most of the imported juice supply to blend with 
their limited local supply in making frozen concentrated orange 
juice 
we will be importing more than 50 percent of our product to 
meet market demand says executive director dan gunter of the 
florida department of citrus imports will probably exceed the 
level of 1985 which when processors needed supply help due to 
cropkilling frosts in december 1983 and january 1985 
production in florida which until 1982 was the world leader in 
citrus is expected to fall sharply due to damage from the 
christmastime freeze the states share of expected us production 
of singlestrength equivalent sse juice which includes 
concentrate chilled and canned juice is seen as falling to about 
45 percent from 706 percent last year 
brazil meanwhile is expected to have a record crop this year 
and export a record 319 million gallons of concentrated juice 
orange processors in california texas and arizona may account 
for only 6 percent of the total us juice supply this year as a 
result domestic orangejuice imports principally from brazil 
will total about 625 million sse gallons according to industry 
economists up 72 percent from the 198889 import level 
at the same time juice prices have risen sharply 
within the past year the wholesale price for brazilian juice 
has risen from 150 a pound to 212 a pound this year and 
because brazil is the worlds largest producerexporter it sets 
the price so consumers will be paying more no matter where their 
juice comes from 
american grocery store prices are expected to average 417 a 
gallon during the current processing season an increase of 124 
percent over the previous year 
particularly ironic to florida industry leaders is that 
processors in this state may take 60 percent of all imported juice 
to blend with the limited local supply in making florida frozen 
concentrated orange juice 
the state expects to pack about 93 million gallons of frozen 
concentrate this year and will import about 93 million gallons 
compared with packing of 175 million gallons and imports of 52 
million gallons in 1989 
the states citrus industry views the imported juice situation 
in a bittersweet vein in good times many bitterly criticize 
brazilian imports although some state processors traditionally buy 
brazilian product to blend with what is considered higherquality 
florida orange juice 
in bad times particularly after frigid weather ices the fruit 
or destroys trees florida depends on brazil to make up the supply 
difference and maintain a steady market and a good price 
floridas problems serve as an impetus for brazil to plant 
more trees and produce a bigger crop says bobby mckown 
executive vice president of florida citrus mutual the states 
largest grower trade association with 12000 members 
this can lead to excess supplies in the future and prices will 
drop and well need to increase demand mckown says brazilian 
imports may help in the shortterm he says but we need to work 
on a longterm basis i dont think brazil is doing enough to 
expand the markets we do most of that after a freeze they just 
clear their inventory 
but gunter said that because of brazils bumper crop and 
floridas shortfall the total amount of orange juice available 
actually may be about the same as last year 
brazils recordhigh price is probably based on an expected 
lower volume for next year gunter said recently brazil 
evidently wants to hold down sales to maintain volume because their 
crop is expected to be smaller next year 
</TEXT>
