<TEXT>
sales of cars and light trucks made in north 
america slumped 79 percent in late february compared with last 
year when consumers rushed to showrooms to snatch up expiring 
incentives automakers said monday 
for the entire month sales of domestic and imported automobiles 
and light trucks were down 47 percent reflecting sagging interest 
in cash rebates and low interest financing that were the rage in 
january and february 1989 
the incentives in early 1989 turned many spring car buyers into 
late winter purchasers 
its not going too bad said sales manager fred voelkel of 
brown and brown chevroletgeo in mesa ariz were down a little 
from last year 
the nine major automakers making vehicles in north america said 
they sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 42688 during 
the feb 2128 period this year compared with a rate of 46336 
during the same time last year 
sales of new cars fell 67 percent and truck sales were down 10 
percent 
for the first two months of this year domestic and overseas 
automakers reported vehicle sales were off 08 percent indicating 
a strong january sales rate was being watered down by a weaker 
february rate 
automakers are keeping a careful eye on their newvehicle 
inventories in anticipation of what they hope will be a return to a 
tradition of a spring buying spree in march and april 
at the beginning of last year automakers advertised the 
incentive programs that expired for the most part at the end of 
february the specter of those programs ending turned likely spring 
buyers into latewinter purchasers grabbing a good deal 
that disrupted the tradition of a sales bulge in march and 
april this year incentives in effect in january and february 
didnt generate the same buying excitement with the notable 
exception of chryslers incentives on minivans in january which 
boosted yeartodate sales figures for 1990 
we are in shape for a good spring said voelkel thats 
when we build up our inventories and build up our advertising a 
little bit 
he said he expects his current 75day supply of cars to swell to 
around 90 days by spring 
gms car and truck sales for late february ran 24 percent 
behind last years pace with car sales off 38 percent and truck 
sales up 09 percent for the entire year gm vehicles sold at a 
pace 02 percent ahead of last year 
fords car and truck sales fell 191 percent in late february 
partly because of strong fleet sales a year ago said robert rewey 
the companys vice president for north american sales 
