<TEXT>
motorola inc on monday unveiled a new computer 
line that the technology company hopes will propel it into the 
industrys major leagues 
but some industry analysts said motorola could end up alienating 
companies that buy its computers for resale under their own brand 
names others questioned whether motorola stands a chance in the 
highly competitive computer field 
motorola is doing so many great things in other parts of the 
company you hate to be negative about their computer effort but i 
dont think it has too much prospect for success said richard l 
whittington of kidder peabody amp co 
the new computers are designed to operate in a network with 
machines made by other companies such as ibm and apple they are 
based on the unix operating system which is becoming the industry 
standard 
motorola said the computers undercut the price of a similar line 
of ibm machines by 35 percent and more while offering comparable 
or better performance the ibm computers which were introduced 
with great fanfare last month were praised by experts for their 
low price relative to peformance 
motorola based in schaumburg ill has made computers for 
years but they primarily have been sold to the federal government 
or to other computer companies that resell them under their own 
names 
the new computers are file servers an increasingly popular 
form of desktop or sideofdesk machine that serves as the central 
data repository for a network of desktop terminals 
analysts generally are impressed by the new motorola computers 
which they said are competitive with the best in the field 
john rymer managing editor of the trade publication unix in the 
office said he believes motorolas strategy is similar to that of 
intel corp a computerchip maker that also makes complete 
computers it sells to third parties for reselling he said these 
chip makers hope to leverage their microprocessor expertise to 
become major computer manufacturers 
some of the companies that buy intel chips to make computers 
have criticized intel for its strategy saying it is not fair for 
their supplier of the most crucial part of a computer to also 
compete in the end product 
however one major user of motorola chips welcomes the companys 
new strategy 
data general corp uses motorolas 88000 chip the same one used 
in the new motorola machines in its computer workstations stan 
dolberg marketing manager for the workstations said the market 
for computers based on this chip is relatively small and additional 
players are needed to help establish it 
nv philips the dutch electronics company uses a relabeled 
motorola computer as the heart of its computer line outside the 
united states philips spokesman cor vraven said he had no comment 
on motorolas strategy because it was his understanding motorola 
had no immediate plan to sell the computers overseas 
however motorola spokeswoman karen simeone said the company 
planned to distribute the computers abroad starting in may 
analysts say motorola needs to improve its marketing and 
distribution to become a major seller of computers in its own 
right to this end the company has launched a 30 million 
advertising campaign 
motorolas machines called the multipersonal computer line 
range in price from about 24000 to 60000 each system comes 
with three desktop screens and a processing unit 
each also is equipped with a localarea network which is a 
cable and related software than allows various computers and 
printers from other companies to be linked 
the new machines which will be available in may are aimed at 
the commercial computer market instead of the engineering and 
scientific customers that often are the target for file servers and 
for workstations which are similar to file servers 
