<TEXT>
the dollar was sharply lower against the japanese 
yen tuesday and the key index on the tokyo stock exchange rebounded 
moderately 
trading remained light during the morning as many investors 
stayed on the sidelines anticipating the bank of japan would 
increase interest rates possibly during the afternoon 
the 225share nikkei stock average recouped 12052 points or 
036 percent ending the morning session at 3396572 on monday 
the index lost 21236 points 
the dollar ended the morning session at 14877 yen down 118 
yen from mondays close it had opened at 14897 yen and weakened 
during the morning as the bank of japan sold dollars actively to 
support its currency 
the yens rebound sparked a rally in the japanese government 
bond market that pushed down interest rates the yield on the 
benchmark no 119 10year bond fell to 7075 percent from 712 
percent late monday 
the dollar continued to weaken in tokyo after falling against 
almost all major currencies in overseas markets earlier following 
internationally coordinated intervention traders said 
central banks from japan britain france and west germany 
bought their own currencies and sold the dollar in an attempt to 
weaken the us currency said toru kanai a foreign exchange 
analyst with new japan securities co 
finance minsiter ryutaro hashimoto told reporters tuesday that 
the framework of international cooperation remains strong and 
coordinated action will continue to be taken to ensure stability in 
foreign exchange markets 
he said us concern over the dollaryen rate was made clear at 
last weekends summit meeting between us president bush and 
japanese prime minster toshiki kaifu in palm springs calif 
in rising above 150 yen in recent days the dollar hit its 
highest level since last june 
the bank of japan was seen selling some 1 billion tuesday 
morning to bolster the yen traders said the central bank does not 
comment on its market intervention activities 
many market players are now trying to reduce their 
dollarholding positions now in case the bank of japan raises its 
discount rate today kanai said 
thats mainly because they speculate there might be a raise 
before central bank governor mr yasushi mieno leaves for europe 
tomorrow and they think there will be no hike while hes gone 
until march 15 he added 
japanese markets have been expecting a discount rate hike to 
stem inflationary pressures ever since the nation held major 
parliamentary elections last month after three hikes last year 
the nations key lending rate stands at 425 percent still the 
lowest among the group of seven industrial nations 
partly as a result of the bank of japans inaction growing 
uncertainties in the market began discouraging stock investment and 
yenbuying causing a rapid decline in share prices and leading to 
a 156910point plunge feb 26 the secondworst fall ever 
on the stock exchange dealers attributed the morning rally to 
the yens strength as well as the rise in the government bond 
prices 
